The bulk test

201 is the magic number — it forces the platform into two chunks and exposes the static-boolean bug that 200 records hides.

@IsTest
private class TriggerBulkTest {

    private static final Integer BULK = 201;

    @TestSetup
    static void setup() {
        List<Account> accts = new List<Account>();
        for (Integer i = 0; i < 50; i++) {
            accts.add(new Account(Name = 'Bulk Acct ' + i));
        }
        insert accts;
    }

    @IsTest
    static void insert201Opportunities_staysWithinLimits() {

        List<Account> accts = [SELECT Id FROM Account];
        List<Opportunity> opps = new List<Opportunity>();

        for (Integer i = 0; i < BULK; i++) {
            opps.add(new Opportunity(
                Name      = 'Bulk Opp ' + i,
                StageName = 'Prospecting',
                CloseDate = Date.today().addDays(30),
                Amount    = 1000,
                AccountId = accts[Math.mod(i, accts.size())].Id
            ));
        }

        Test.startTest();
        insert opps;                                  // ← 2 chunks: 200 + 1
        Test.stopTest();

        // every record processed — this is what a naive static boolean breaks
        Assert.areEqual(BULK, [SELECT COUNT() FROM Task WHERE Subject LIKE 'Kickoff call:%'],
            'All 201 records must produce a Task, not just the first chunk of 200');

        // the service's own footprint, captured via @TestVisible statics
        Assert.isTrue(OpportunityService.lastQueryCount <= 2,
            'Rollup must stay at 2 SOQL regardless of volume');
    }

    @IsTest
    static void bulkUpdate_rollupIsCorrect() {

        Account a = new Account(Name = 'Rollup Target');
        insert a;

        List<Opportunity> opps = new List<Opportunity>();
        for (Integer i = 0; i < BULK; i++) {
            opps.add(new Opportunity(
                Name = 'Rollup ' + i, StageName = 'Prospecting',
                CloseDate = Date.today().addDays(10), Amount = 100, AccountId = a.Id
            ));
        }
        insert opps;

        for (Opportunity o : opps) o.StageName = 'Closed Won';

        Test.startTest();
        update opps;
        Test.stopTest();

        Account result = [SELECT Won_Revenue__c, Open_Opp_Count__c FROM Account WHERE Id = :a.Id];
        Assert.areEqual(BULK * 100, result.Won_Revenue__c, 'Sum must include all 201 chunks');
        Assert.areEqual(0, result.Open_Opp_Count__c);
    }

    @IsTest
    static void validationBlocksClosureWithOpenTasks() {

        Case c = new Case(Subject = 'Test', Status = 'New');
        insert c;
        insert new Task(WhatId = c.Id, Subject = 'Open item', Status = 'Not Started');

        c.Status = 'Closed';
        c.Description = 'Resolved';

        Test.startTest();
        try {
            update c;
            Assert.fail('Expected DmlException');
        } catch (DmlException e) {
            Assert.isTrue(e.getDmlMessage(0).contains('open task'), e.getDmlMessage(0));
        }
        Test.stopTest();
    }

    @IsTest
    static void defaultsApplyWithoutDml() {
        // service tested directly — no database, runs in ~5ms
        List<Account> accts = new List<Account>{ new Account(Name = '  Padded  ') };
        AccountService.applyDefaults(accts);

        Assert.areEqual('Padded', accts[0].Name);
        Assert.areEqual('Prospect', accts[0].Type);
        Assert.areEqual('India', accts[0].BillingCountry);
    }
}

Two things about that first assertion. Assert.areEqual(BULK, ...) on the Task count is the only assertion that catches the chunking bug — a hasRun boolean would produce 200 Tasks and pass any test using 200 records. And the @TestVisible static Integer lastQueryCount trick is how you assert on the trigger's internal limit consumption; Limits.getQueries() in the test method itself measures the test context, not the trigger's, which is why people usually can't prove bulk safety and just hope.

The last test is the payoff for the handler/service split — no DML, no @TestSetup, no trigger. Pure function call. In a mature org that's where most of your coverage should live, with a handful of DML-based tests proving the wiring.

What changed, summarized
	                                                                               Before	                                                    After
Trigger body	                                          routing logic, isBefore/isInsert chains	                                           2 lines
Logic location	                                       static methods on a "handler" that took Trigger.new	                               service methods taking plain collections
Testability	                                           required DML to invoke anything	                                                   services callable in-memory
Recursion	                                             none, or a bare boolean	                                                           Set<Id> guard + change-detection
Rollup cost	                                           scaled with record count	                                                           fixed 2 SOQL / 2 DML
Bypass	                                               impossible	                                                                         TriggerHandler.bypass('X')
Reparenting	                                           parent A left stale	                                                               union of old + new parent Ids

The natural continuation from here is async — the kickoff-task creation is a reasonable candidate for a Queueable once you're chaining more work, and that's where Test.startTest/stopTest stops being boilerplate and starts being load-bearing.

